  "narrative": {
    "executive_view": "Payroll processing has abundant AI/RPA task exposure, but local bureaus face scale platforms and embedded fintech. Regulatory liability and money movement preserve an intermediary, though often the platform rather than the acquirable bureau [S1].",
    "how_ai_changes_work": "Payroll platforms are investing in generative AI and automate routine compliance, calculation and client workflows [S1]. Human exception handling, tax notices and client relationships remain; the supplied CPA-heavy occupation mix omits payroll clerks and is a material proxy caveat.",
    "value_capture": "PEPM recurring pricing can retain automation gains, but ADP’s recurring-revenue platform, long retention and client-funds capabilities show the scale advantage local bureaus face [S1]. Competitive platforms can pass savings through, so capture is moderate rather than assumed.",
    "adoption_timing": "Platform payroll is already digital and ADP reports generative-AI investment [S1]. Effective automation is estimated above 50%, so t50 is zero, although independent bureaus may lag the platforms.",
    "consolidation_economics": "The deterministic screen has 297 target-band firms, but small bureaus face fixed compliance costs and channel dependence. Active platform consolidation is not used as AI-adoption evidence and multiples remain low-confidence.",
    "terminal_demand": "Paid payroll intermediation is durable because multi-state remittance, custody, reporting-agent responsibility and exception handling remain costly. The local bureau is pressured by platform oligopoly, which is distinct from the survival of payroll processing.",
    "risks_and_uncertainty": "Labor share is unusually high and compares different vintages; revenue can net client funds. The supplied 5412 mix is not payroll-specific. No reopened independent-bureau price or transaction census supports precise capture or multiples."
  },
